.SH NAME
\fB
\fBATSlog gives the convenient interface for viewing and analysing bells of various models PBX.
\fB
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.fam C

\fBatslogd\fP [\fB-D\fP \fIdir\fP] [\fB-L\fP \fIlogfile\fP] [\fB-s\fP \fIspeed\fP] [\fB-c\fP \fIcsize\fP]
[\fB-p\fP \fIparity\fP] [\fB-f\fP \fIsbits\fP] [\fB-t\fP \fItype\fP] [\fB-P\fP PIDfile][\fB-d\fP]
[\fB-e\fP] [\fB-a\fP] [\fB-o\fP] [\fB-i\fP \fIaddress\fP] [\fItcp:port\fP] \fIdev\fP
.fam T
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION

CDR Reader for PBXs v.1.09 for the ATSlog version @version@ build @buildnumber@ www.atslog.dp.ua
.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.B
\fB-D\fP \fIdir\fP
directory where CDR files will be put, default is current \fIdir\fP
.TP
.B
\fB-L\fP \fIlogfile\fP
file for error messages, default is stderr
.TP
.B
\fB-F\fP filename
name of file where CDR messages will be put
.TP
.B
\fB-s\fP \fIspeed\fP
\fIspeed\fP of serial device, default 9600
.TP
.B
\fB-c\fP char_size
length of character; valid values from 5 to 8
.TP
.B
\fB-p\fP \fIparity\fP
\fIparity\fP of serial device:
e - even \fIparity\fP, o - odd \fIparity\fP, n - no \fIparity\fP,
.TP
.B
\fB-f\fP stop_bits
number of stop bits; valid values 1 or 2
.TP
.B
\fB-d\fP
output additional debug messages
.TP
.B
\fB-e\fP
copy error messages to stderr (in case if \fB-L\fP has value)
.TP
.B
\fB-a\fP
write date at the beginning of file (for Definity \fItype\fP only)
.TP
.B
\fB-o\fP
write CDR additionally to stdout
.TP
.B
\fB-m\fP
write log files on month-by-month instead of day-by-day basis
.TP
.B
\fB-n\fP
consider day in place of month and vice versa
.TP
.B
\fB-x\fP number
maximum number of clients for TCP connections (default: 1)
see /etc/hosts.allow, /etc/hosts.deny)
.TP
.B
\fB-w\fP seconds
timeout before I/O port will be opened next time after EOF
.TP
.B
\fB-i\fP \fIaddress\fP
IP \fIaddress\fP of interface for bind only to it
(default to all interfaces)
.TP
.B
\fItcp:port\fP
where port is a TCP port for listen on.
.TP
.B
\fB-b\fP
become daemon
.TP
.B
\fB-P\fP
PID file. /var/run/atslogd.pid by default
.PP
Use libwrap for contol access to TCP connections. See /etc/hosts.allow and /etc/hosts.deny
